0001: # FARM RX — BUILD HANDOFF
0002: ### A customer-facing farm management platform, by Crop RX Solutions
0003:
0004: **Hand this document to a fresh build session. It is self-contained.**
0005:
0006: - **Product name:** Farm Rx
0007: - **Parent brand:** Crop RX Solutions (Robinson, IL)
0008: - **Audience:** Corn / soybean / wheat growers in southeastern Illinois & western Indiana
0009: - **Owner:** Mason Wells
0010: - **Status:** Greenfield build. Nothing exists yet except the CRX Manager codebase to port from.
0011:
0012: ---
0013:
0014: ## PART 0 — THE THREE RULES
0015:
0016: Every decision in this build defers to these.
0017:
0018: **RULE 1 — Simplicity beats features.**
0019: The user is a 55-year-old farmer, in a truck, in July sun, possibly with gloves on, possibly without his reading glasses. He is *not* tech-savvy and he will abandon this app the first time it confuses him.
0020: - Base font **18px**, not 14px. Tap targets **48px minimum**.
0021: - All numbers in tabular figures (`font-variant-numeric: tabular-nums`) so bushels and dollars align in columns.
0022: - **Two-tap rule:** any common action reachable in two taps.
0023: - Plain English everywhere. If a screen needs a manual, it's wrong.
0024:
0025: **RULE 2 — The data is theirs, and they must be able to SEE that it's theirs.**
0026: Farm Rx is Crop RX-branded, but a farmer's grain position is the most private number on his farm. If the software is named after his chemical supplier, he will quietly wonder whether his supplier can see what he made. Kill that doubt explicitly:
0027: - Grain and financial modules default to **PRIVATE**.
0028: - An explicit per-farm toggle: **"Share my grain position with my Crop RX rep — OFF."**
0029: - Enforced in the database with Postgres Row Level Security, not just in the UI.
0030: - Build this on day one. It is a signup driver, not a setting.
0031:
0032: **RULE 3 — Brand the wrapper, never the buttons.**
0033: The RX personality lives in the name, the login screen, the ℞ icon, and the green. It does **not** live in the navigation. Nav items are: *Fields. Grain. Inventory. Profitability. Equipment. Tasks.* **Never** call the dashboard "Vitals" or records "The Chart." The medical metaphor will feel clever for ten minutes and will cost real users forever.
0034:
0035: ---
0036:
0037: ## PART 1 — STACK & PLATFORM
0038:
0039: - **Frontend:** React + TypeScript
0040: - **Backend / DB / Auth:** Supabase (Postgres + Row Level Security + Auth)
0041: - **Hosting:** Vercel
0042: - **Charts:** Recharts
0043: - **Delivery:** **PWA — not the app stores.**
0044:
0045: ### Why PWA (decided)
0046: No App Store review, no Apple developer account, no 30% cut, **instant updates** (critical when fixing a bug during planting), one codebase, installable to the home screen with the ℞ icon, works offline in bad cell coverage. iOS supports Web Push for installed PWAs, so alerts work. Wrap in Capacitor later *only if* app-store presence becomes necessary. **Mobile-first is not a nice-to-have — most sessions will be on a phone.**
0047:
0048: ### Offline tolerance is a hard requirement
0049: Rural connectivity is bad. Never lose a half-entered sale, spray record, or scouting note because a bar dropped. Queue writes locally and sync.
0050:
0051: ### RLS is the technical backbone of Rule 2
0052: Every table is farm-scoped. A Crop RX rep sees a farm's private data **only** if that farm flipped the share toggle. Mason's prior CRX Manager audits surfaced RLS holes — treat this as a known risk area and get the policies independently reviewed before any customer touches it.
0053:
0054: ---
0055:
0056: ## PART 2 — CROP TYPES (get this right in the schema first)
0057:
0058: Supported crops:
0059: - **Yellow Corn**
0060: - **White Corn**
0061: - **Conventional Corn (Non-GMO)**
0062: - **Soybeans**
0063: - **Double-Crop Soybeans**
0064: - **Wheat**
0065:
0066: **Critical, non-obvious:** White corn and Non-GMO corn are **not "yellow corn with a tag."** They carry:
0067: - their own **premiums** ($/bu over the board),
0068: - their own **buyers** (fewer of them),
0069: - **identity-preserved delivery requirements** (segregated bins, segregated trucks).
0070:
0071: Model them as **distinct marketable commodities** with their own contracts, premiums, and cash bids. A contract for white corn is not interchangeable with a contract for yellow corn. Getting this wrong is a painful retrofit.
0072:
0073: **Double-crop soybeans** mean a single field carries **two crops in one year** (wheat, then DC beans). Do not model crop as a column on the field. Model **crop assignments as their own rows** keyed to `field_id + year + crop`. This breaks naive schemas and is expensive to fix later.
0074:
0075: ---
0076:
0077: ## PART 3 — THE MODULES
0078:
0079: Build in this order. **Do not build them all at once — that is how farm software projects die.**
0080:
0081: ---
0082:
0083: ### MODULE 1 — FIELDS *(foundation — build first)*
0084:
0085: Everything else reads from here.
0086:
0087: **Port the engine from CRX Manager.** The field / acre / billing-split logic already exists in Mason's CRX Manager app. Analyze that repo and reuse the schema and logic rather than rebuilding from scratch. *(A preliminary task for this build is to point Claude Code at the CRX Manager repo and extract/document the reusable Fields and Inventory engines.)*
0088:
0089: **Objects:**
0090: - **Field** — name, location/legal description, total acres, FSA farm/tract number (optional), soil productivity index (optional).
0091: - **Crop assignment** — `field_id + year + crop + planted_acres`. Multiple rows per field per year (see double-crop above).
0092: - **Arrangement** (per field) — how the ground is held:
0093:   - Owned
0094:   - Cash rent (fixed $/acre)
0095:   - Flex cash rent (base + configurable bonus formula on price / yield / revenue)
0096:   - Crop share — **2/3–1/3, 60/40, 50/50, custom** (store landlord % of crop AND landlord % of each specified input)
0097: - **Entity** — fields roll up to an operating entity. Mason runs several (Wells Farm Group, Next Generation Farms, etc.). Support multiple entities per user and **filter every report by entity.**
0098:
0099: **Screens:** field list (sortable by crop/entity/arrangement, with total-acre stat boxes at top) · field detail (crop history, arrangement, acres, yield history) · fast add/edit.
0100:
0101: **Feeds:** planted acres → expected bushels (Module 2). Arrangement + acres → share economics (Module 4).
0102:
0103: ---
0104:
0105: ### MODULE 2 — GRAIN: HEDGING & SALES *(the flagship — give it the most polish)*
0106:
0107: **This is the module that makes farmers log in daily. It is the reason the product exists. A dedicated, well-built page.**
0108:
0109: #### 2.1 Expected production (auto-calculated)
0110: - Pull planted acres by crop from Fields.
0111: - × **APH / expected yield** per crop (user-set, editable per field, sensible defaults).
0112: - → **expected bushels** per crop, per entity, per whole farm.
0113: - Handle double-crop soybeans as their own production line.
0114: - Handle white / non-GMO corn as **separate commodities** with their own expected production.
0115:
0116: #### 2.2 The projected → actual switch *(explicit requirement)*
0117: Every production figure has two states, toggled per crop:
0118: - **Projected** (pre-harvest) = acres × expected yield
0119: - **Actual** (post-harvest) = real harvested bushels
0120:
0121: The marketing plan, % sold, and breakevens **recalculate against whichever is live.** Pre-harvest the farmer markets against projected; at harvest he flips to actual and everything downstream updates.
0122:
0123: **Store both. Never overwrite projected with actual** — both are needed for season review. Design as `expected_bushels` + `actual_bushels` + a per-crop flag choosing which drives the math.
0124:
0125: Actual bushels arrive from: yield-monitor import (Module 7) or manual entry.
0126:
0127: #### 2.3 Market data *(see PART 4 for the vendor decision)*
0128: - **Futures:** delayed CBOT quotes — corn (ZC), soybeans (ZS), Chicago wheat (ZW). Front months plus new-crop contracts (Dec corn, Nov beans, Jul wheat).
0129: - **Local cash bids:** nearest elevators by farm ZIP — elevator name, cash price, basis, delivery window.
0130: - **Delayed is fine and decided.** Label the delay in the UI.
0131: - Cache server-side. Never call the API per page load.
0132:
0133: #### 2.4 Position view — the heart of the page
0134: Per crop, at a glance:
0135: - Total production (projected or actual)
0136: - Bushels **priced vs. unpriced** (both bushels and %)
0137: - **Average sold price**
0138: - **Blended expected revenue** = (sold bu × sold price) + (unsold bu × live board/cash)
0139: - **Overlaid against BOTH:**
0140:   - **Breakeven** (from Module 4)
0141:   - **Crop insurance guarantee** (see 2.7)
0142:
0143: The single sentence a farmer should be able to read in two seconds:
0144: > *"I'm 62% priced at $4.71. Breakeven is $4.28. Insurance floor is $4.31. 47,500 bu still open with Dec at $4.68."*
0145:
0146: #### 2.5 Contracts
0147: Log a sale in ~15 seconds. **Contract types (final list — no options):**
0148: - **Cash / spot**
0149: - **Forward cash**
0150: - **Basis**
0151: - **HTA (Hedged-to-Arrive)**
0152:
0153: Fields: buyer/elevator (prefill from the cash-bid list), commodity, bushels, price (or futures + basis), delivery window, contract #, premium (for white/non-GMO). Editable, running list, clear total.
0154:
0155: *Options contracts are explicitly OUT of scope.*
0156:
0157: #### 2.6 Marketing plan targets + alerts
0158: - Farmer sets a plan: *"sell 10% at $4.80, another 10% at $5.00, 20% by Sept 1."*
0159: - Track progress against the plan.
0160: - **Alert when a price or date target is hit** — in-app + email.
0161: - This is what grain marketing advisors charge thousands a year for. It's the stickiest feature in the app.
0162:
0163: #### 2.7 Crop insurance guarantee
0164: Store per unit: **APH, coverage level, revenue guarantee $/acre → guarantee $/bu.**
0165: Overlay it on the position view. Without it a farmer marketing against breakeven alone is seeing half the picture. This is what separates a real marketing tool from a spreadsheet.
0166:
0167: #### 2.8 Grain bin / storage inventory
0168: - Bushels in each bin. On-farm vs. commercial storage.
0169: - **Committed vs. free** bushels.
0170: - Segregation matters for white / non-GMO (identity-preserved).
0171: - The hedging page is fiction without knowing what's actually sitting unpriced in a bin.
0172:
0173: #### 2.9 Basis history charts
0174: Historical basis by elevator and commodity. Answers the question that actually drives the decision: *"is basis historically strong or weak right now?"* Store every cash bid you pull; the history builds itself.
0175:
0176: #### 2.10 USDA report calendar
0177: WASDE, Grain Stocks, Prospective Plantings, Crop Progress. Farmers plan marketing around these dates. Simple calendar + optional reminder. USDA publishes the schedule publicly.
0178:
0179: #### 2.11 Compliance
0180: Farm Rx shows **numbers and the farmer's own targets.** It never says "sell now." Both Bushel and Harvest Profit are explicit that they do not offer marketing advice. Add a plain-language disclaimer on the Grain and Profitability pages. **Mason is not a licensed advisor and the product must not imply otherwise.**
0181:
0182: ---
0183:
0184: ### MODULE 3 — INVENTORY, SPRAY RECORDS & EPA COMPLIANCE
0185:
0186: **Port and simplify from CRX Manager.** Farmers abandon complex inventory tools — keep this lean.
0187:
0188: #### 3.1 Products
0189: - Chemical, seed, fertilizer, other inputs.
0190: - **Two sources:** (a) delivered by Crop RX, (b) **added by the farmer himself** (bought elsewhere). Both tracked.
0191: - Tracking the farmer's *whole shed* — not just CRX purchases — is exactly what makes this a real compliance tool rather than a sales gimmick. Mirror CRX Manager's approach.
0192:
0193: #### 3.2 Future CRX Manager sync *(design for it, don't build it yet)*
0194: Eventually: a delivery entered in CRX Manager **auto-appears** in that customer's Farm Rx inventory. Design the schema now so this drops in cleanly — shared product IDs, a delivery-event table. **Do not build the sync in v1. Do not block it either.**
0195:
0196: #### 3.3 Spray records / EPA compliance
0197: Log applications: product(s), rate, **EPA reg #**, date, field, applicator, target pest, weather at application, REI/PHI. Pull product + EPA reg data from the inventory item so the farmer never retypes a reg number. Reuse the compliance-record structure from CRX Manager.
0198:
0199: #### 3.4 Chemical-needed planner
0200: - Given fields + planned programs → **how much product is needed to cover the farm.**
0201: - As applications are logged, **draw down** needed/on-hand.
0202: - Simple visual: **planned vs. applied vs. remaining**, per product, per acre remaining.
0203: - Prevents the mid-season "we're short" phone call.
0204:
0205: #### 3.5 Nutrient removal calculator
0206: Bushels harvested → **lbs of N / P / K removed** per field. Standard removal coefficients per crop. Feeds next year's fertility plan — and it's a direct, natural hook back into Crop RX's agronomy business.
0207:
0208: #### 3.6 Costs → Profitability
0209: Inventory product costs feed Module 4's input-cost entry so chemical and seed costs are never entered twice.
0210:
0211: ---
0212:
0213: ### MODULE 4 — PROFITABILITY & SCENARIOS
0214:
0215: A dedicated page. This produces the artifact a farmer hands his banker and his landlord.
0216:
0217: #### 4.1 Input costs (per crop)
0218: Per-acre categories: seed, fertilizer, chemical, fuel, labor/custom, crop insurance, cash rent, equipment/depreciation, interest, other. **Pull chemical and seed costs from Inventory** where available.
0219:
0220: Support **2–3 comparable scenarios side by side** (e.g. "high fertilizer," "reduced pass," "aggressive yield").

