0231: #### 4.3 Breakeven
0232: - Per crop, per field, per whole farm.
0233: - **Breakeven $/bu = total cost per acre ÷ expected yield per acre.**
0234: - Recalculates live as inputs, yield, or arrangement change.
0235: - **Feeds back into the Grain page** as the overlay line (2.4).
0236:
0237: #### 4.4 PROFITABILITY MATRIX ⭐ *(the signature element — build this well)*
0238: A grid / heat map:
0239: - **X axis: grain price** (range around the current board)
0240: - **Y axis: yield** (range around expected)
0241: - **Each cell: profit or loss per acre** at that price × yield, given the scenario's input costs
0242: - **Shade it:** green above breakeven, red below, a bright **breakeven contour line** between
0243: - **Interactive:** change scenario or inputs → matrix updates live
0244:
0245: This one visual is worth more to a farmer than ten reports. Make it the memorable thing about the page.
0246:
0247: #### 4.5 Cost per acre BY FIELD
0248: Falls out of this module nearly free — and most farmers genuinely do not know which fields make money and which ones bleed. **This is the number that changes what they're willing to cash-rent.** Surface it prominently.
0249:
0250: #### 4.6 Reports
0251: Every profitability view exports to a **clean, Crop RX-branded PDF.** This PDF is a marketing asset and a sales tool — treat its polish as a feature. Mason has an existing ReportLab-based branded PDF pipeline (the tank-label system); reuse that branding approach and token set.
0252:
0253: ---
0254:
0255: ### MODULE 5 — EQUIPMENT & MAINTENANCE
0256:
0257: Mason runs ~22 semis (Detroit Diesel / Paccar), a RoGator 1100C sprayer fleet, a Case IH 8250 combine, a MacDon FD145 header, and a Stealth ZD tile plow. His customers have comparable fleets.
0258:
0259: - **Asset record:** make, model, year, serial/VIN, purchase date, purchase price.
0260: - **Hours / miles** tracking.
0261: - **Service intervals** with reminders (oil change, filters, DEF, inspections) — reminders push to the Task Board (Module 6).
0262: - **Repair history** — date, work performed, parts, cost, vendor.
0263: - **Warranty** tracking with expiration alerts.
0264: - **Cost per machine** — rolls into Profitability equipment costs.
0265: - Document/photo attachment (receipts, manuals).
0266:
0267: *Optional / assess later:* DOT fleet compliance (DVIRs, IFTA, CDL and medical-card expirations). Relevant for a 22-truck fleet but a distinct problem domain — confirm with Mason before building.
0268:
0269: ---
0270:
0271: ### MODULE 6 — TASK BOARD
0272:
0273: Port the concept from CRX Manager.
0274:
0275: - Create tasks, **assign to employees**, set due dates.
0276: - **Tie tasks to fields and equipment** (*"spray Field 12," "service Truck 7"*).
0277: - Reminders / notifications (in-app + email).
0278: - Simple status: To Do → Doing → Done.
0279: - Employee logins with restricted permissions (an employee must NOT see the grain position).
0280: - Service intervals from Module 5 auto-generate tasks.
0281:
0282: Keep it dead simple. This is a farm crew, not a software team. No sprints, no story points, no swimlanes.
0283:
0284: ---
0285:
0286: ### MODULE 7 — MACHINE DATA IMPORT ⭐ *(strategically important — read the build note)*
0287:
0288: Farmers must be able to bring in **planting and harvest data** from **Climate FieldView, John Deere Operations Center, and AgFiniti (Ag Leader).**
0289:
0290: This feeds:
0291: - **Actual harvested bushels** → Module 2.2 (the projected→actual switch)
0292: - **Seed variety by field** → 7.2
0293: - **Planting dates** → GDD/crop staging → 7.3
0294: - As-applied data → spray records (Module 3.3)
0295:
0296: #### 7.1 How to build it — READ THIS BEFORE STARTING
0297:
0298: **Do NOT build three separate OAuth integrations.** Each vendor requires separate developer registration, partner approval, and its own OAuth flow. John Deere's Operations Center API requires app registration, an OAuth handshake, and the user *separately* adjusting permissions at `connections.deere.com`. Climate FieldView requires its own client ID / client secret / API key and a "Log in with FieldView" OAuth flow. That's weeks of work plus vendor approval cycles.
0299:
0300: **Use middleware instead. `Leaf` (leafagriculture) abstracts John Deere, Climate FieldView, and Trimble behind ONE API** with normalized **Plant / Apply / Harvest** operations. It handles the per-vendor OAuth and returns standardized data. This collapses the entire problem into a single integration.
0301:
0302: **Phase it:**
0303: - **Phase A (v1):** **File upload.** The farmer exports a shapefile/CSV from FieldView, Ops Center, or AgFiniti and uploads it. Works immediately. Zero partnerships, zero approvals, zero OAuth. **Ship this.**
0304: - **Phase B:** Add **Leaf** for live sync once there are paying users. Verify Leaf's AgFiniti / Ag Leader coverage during Phase B — if unsupported, keep file upload for AgFiniti.
0305:
0306: *Useful note: John Deere Operations Center can already ingest FieldView data via its Connections tool, so a single Deere integration may transitively cover FieldView users who have linked the two.*
0307:
0308: #### 7.2 Seed variety tracking
0309: - Hybrid/variety by field — **auto-populated from planter as-planted data**, or **manually tagged** if the farmer has no monitor.
0310: - Link **variety → field → yield** so the farmer can answer *"what did that hybrid actually make on that ground?"*
0311: - Multi-year variety performance history.
0312:
0313: #### 7.3 Growing degree days / crop staging
0314: - GDD accumulation per field from **planting date** (auto from planter data, or manual).
0315: - Predict growth stage (V-stages, R-stages).
0316: - Drives timing decisions — fungicide passes, post-emerge windows. Natural hook back to Crop RX agronomy.
0317: - Needs a temperature source. **The NWS API is free** and sufficient.
0318:
0319: ---
0320:
0321: ## PART 4 — MARKET DATA: THE DECISION
0322:
0323: Mason wants delayed futures **and** local elevator cash bids. These are two different problems.
0324:
0325: ### Futures — easy and cheap
0326: Delayed CBOT quotes for corn, soybeans, wheat are widely available:
0327: - **API Ninjas** — free tier gives 15-minute delayed data in bushels with OHLCV history *(note: the free tier rotates a limited set of commodities weekly — verify corn/beans/wheat availability, or take the cheap paid tier)*
0328: - **CommodityPriceAPI** — Lite tier: 2,000 calls/month, 10-minute updates
0329: - **Databento** — licensed CBOT distributor, carries ZC/ZW/ZS, offers free starting credits
0330:
0331: Any of these covers it for roughly $0–30/month. **Not a blocker.**
0332:
0333: ### Cash bids — this is the real problem
0334: **There is no free source of local elevator cash bids, and here is why:** DTN collects 36,000–40,000 bids per day from 4,200 grain buyers, gathered **by phone** — a dozen staff literally calling elevators every market day. They're explicit that competitors mostly *scrape* websites, and that scraped prices may be stale or merely "posted" rather than what the buyer will actually pay. Barchart scrapes. AgWeb's public cash-bid tool is Barchart underneath.
0335:
0336: **Options:**
0337:
0338: | Option | Cost | Verdict |
0339: |---|---|---|
0340: | **Barchart OnDemand** — `getGrainBids` returns the ~30 nearest elevators to a ZIP with name, price, basis, delivery window, contact | ~$650/yr | **Recommended.** Works immediately. |
0341: | **DTN Grain Bids API** | Quote-based, likely higher | Better data (phoned, not scraped) but requires a site ID + portal config. Enterprise-y. |
0342: | **Scrape local elevators yourself** | $0 + maintenance | Tempting — only ~15 elevators matter, not national coverage. But scrapers break silently, several elevators serve bids from third-party widgets behind session cookies and anti-forgery tokens, and it likely violates ToS. Debugging a broken parser during planting is a bad trade. |
0343:
0344: ### The phased plan (decided)
0345: 1. **v1:** Free/cheap futures API + **manual basis entry** (farmer types his local bid once). Ships now, costs nothing, proves the product.
0346: 2. **v2:** Add **Barchart** (~$650/yr ≈ $54/month) once there are paying users. Ten customers at $10/month covers it. **Do not scrape.**
0347: 3. **Abstract the market-data layer behind an internal service interface** so the vendor can be swapped without touching UI code.
0348:
0349: **Hard gate before building the cash-bid feed:** confirm **in writing** with Barchart that their license permits displaying elevator cash bids to end-user farmers inside a commercial application. *(This is a real legal question — get it confirmed by Barchart, and ideally by counsel, before committing dev time.)*
0350:
0351: ---
0352:
0353: ## PART 5 — BRAND
0354:
0355: Use these verbatim. They come from Crop RX's existing print standards — which means every customer already recognizes this visual language from the tank labels they've been handed for years.
0356:
0357: ```
0358: CRX_GREEN     #28A26A   Primary buttons, active nav, positive values, total bars
0359: DEEP_GREEN    #218A5C   Section headers, secondary emphasis
0360: CHARCOAL      #2E2E2E   Primary text
0361: MATTE_GRAY    #4E4E4E   Labels, secondary text
0362: LIGHT_GREEN   #E8F5EE   KPI / stat card backgrounds
0363: PREMIX_BG     #F5F5F5   Table zebra striping, page background
0364: WARN_RED      #C62828   Overdue, unpriced, below-breakeven, late compliance
0365: WARN_BG       #FFF3E0   Alert card fill
0366:
0367: --- Added for app use (not in the print set) ---
0368: CHROME_GREEN  #17513A   Deep green for large surfaces (sidebar). #218A5C vibrates at full height.
0369: AMBER         #E8A33D   "Heads up" state. NOT everything non-green can be red — if it is,
0370:                         farmers tune red out within a week and miss the one that mattered.
0371: HAIRLINE      #E3E6E4   Borders / dividers
0372: ```
0373:
0374: - **Radius:** 16px on cards (matches the print tank-label cards)
0375: - **Type:** Helvetica-style face for headings and the logo lockup (matches existing labels). **Inter** for body and **all numbers**, with `tabular-nums`.
0376: - **Logo:** `https://croprxsolutions.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/logo-1.png` (960×300)
0377: - **Slogan:** `INNOVATIVE SOLUTIONS. UNMATCHED RESULTS.`
0378:
0379: ### The co-branding lockup (important)
0380: - **The farm's own logo goes TOP-LEFT** in the sidebar. This is *their* software.
0381: - **The Crop RX mark is pinned to the BOTTOM of the sidebar** — "Powered by Crop RX." Always visible, never in the way.
0382: - If the farm uploads no logo, **fall back to their farm name in bold.** Never leave the slot empty.
0383: - **The login screen is the one place to go full CRX brand:** large ℞ / "Farm Rx" mark, CRX green, the slogan, and *"by Crop RX Solutions."* The instant they log in, it becomes their farm and Crop RX steps back to a footer mark.
0384: - That hierarchy shift is what makes the co-branding feel like a gift instead of a leash. It is also what makes Rule 2 credible.
0385:
0386: **A working HTML mockup** (dashboard + login, real tokens, real logo, co-branding lockup, stat boxes, alert card, data table, total bar) accompanies this handoff — use it as the visual reference. *Note: the mockup file is labeled "Rx One"; the name is now **Farm Rx**. All tokens and layout still apply.*
0387:
0388: ### Design note
0389: The stat boxes, `DEEP_GREEN` section headers, zebra-striped tables, `WARN_RED` alert boxes, and `CRX_GREEN` total bars in this app are **lifted directly from Crop RX's existing tank labels.** Customers have been reading this interface for years without knowing it was software. Preserve that.
0390:
0391: ---
0392:
0393: ## PART 6 — BUILD ORDER
0394:
0395: 1. **Preliminary:** Point Claude Code at the CRX Manager repo. Extract and document the reusable **Fields** (acres, billing splits) and **Inventory** (products, spray records, EPA compliance) engines.
0396: 2. **Module 1 — Fields.** Nothing works without acres.
0397: 3. **Module 2 — Grain.** The daily-use hook. Start with manual entry + free futures + manual basis.
0398: 4. **Module 4 — Profitability.** Ties Fields + Grain together. Produces the banker PDF.
0399: 5. **Module 3 — Inventory & compliance.**
0400: 6. **Modules 5 & 6 — Equipment & Tasks.**
0401: 7. **Module 7 — Machine data import.** Phase A (file upload) can land earlier if it unblocks actual-bushel entry.
0402:
0403: **Ship Fields + a usable Grain page in front of a handful of real Crop RX customers before building the rest.** Their reaction will reorder everything below it. This is the most important sentence in this document.
0404:
0405: ---
0406:
0407: ## PART 7 — EXPLICITLY OUT OF SCOPE
0408:
0409: Considered and cut. Do not build:
0410: - Options contracts (puts/calls/collars) — cash, forward, basis, and HTA only
0411: - Weather / spray-window alerts
0412: - Landlord portal
0413: - App store distribution (PWA instead)
0414: - Scraping elevator websites
0415:
0416: **Roadmap — not now, but do not design in a way that blocks:**
0417: - Soil test storage per field *(Mason has an existing Kinsey-Albrecht interpreter to plug in)*
0418: - CRX Manager → Farm Rx delivery sync
0419: - Barchart cash-bid feed
0420: - Leaf live machine-data sync
0421: - DOT / fleet compliance
0422:
0423: ---
0424:
0425: ## PART 8 — OPEN QUESTIONS FOR MASON
0426:
0427: 1. **Scale tickets / load tracking** — 22 semis, and this was never decided. Ticket in/out, truck, field, buyer. It's the other natural source of actual harvested bushels alongside yield-monitor import. In or out?
0428: 2. **Prepay balance tracking** — Crop RX already processes prepay invoices, and farmers prepay for tax reasons. Showing a prepay balance and what it's drawn against ties Farm Rx to the invoicing. In or out?
0429: 3. **Pricing model** — free to Crop RX customers, or a subscription? Determines whether the $650 Barchart cost is trivially covered.
0430: 4. **Employee permissions** — how granular? At minimum, an employee must NOT see the grain position or financials.

